<HEADLINE>
<P>
WHERE TO LEARN ABOUT BONSAI 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN HEEGER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Resources for local bonsai enthusiasts include the following societies: 
</P>
<P>
 * Sansui-kai of Southern California meets at 7:30 p.m. the last Wednesday of 
the month at Western Federal Savings & Loan, 17660 Ventura Blvd., Encino. Call 
Dwain Petersen, (818) 368-4371. 
</P>
<P>
 * Descanso Bonsai Society meets at 7:30 p.m. the third Tuesday of the month in 
Van de Kamp Hall at Descanso Gardens, 1418 Descanso Drive, La Canada 
Flintridge. Call Martin L. Mann, (818) 786-6168. Publications recommended by 
Fuji Bonsai Nursery include: 
</P>
<P>
 * Bonsai Today, a magazine published every two months by Stone Lantern 
Publishing Co., Department S, P.O. Box 816, Sudbury, MA 01776, telephone (508) 
443-7110. 
</P>
<P>
 * Bonsai: The Journal of the American Bonsai Society, Box 358, Keene, NH 
03431. 
</P>
<P>
 * Bonsai Clubs International, a quarterly magazine. Write Virginia Ellermann, 
2636 W. Mission Road, No. 277, Tallahassee, FL 32304-2556. 
</P>
<P>
 * Golden Statements -- the Bonsai Magazine. Write Marie Rohde, 6385 Zulmida 
Ave., Newark, CA 94560. 
</P>
<P>
 * "Bonsai Techniques I," a basic, comprehensive manual by Los Angeles bonsai 
master John Yoshio Naka; published by the Bonsai Institute of California, P.O. 
Box 6268, Whittier 90609-6268. SUSAN HEEGER 
</P>
