<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONDITION OF LUKAS IS UPGRADED TO FAIR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thoroughbred trainer Jeff Lukas made further progress Thursday from injuries 
suffered when he was hit by a runaway horse Dec. 15. 
</P>
<P>
 His condition has been upgraded to fair. 
</P>
<P>
 Lukas, 36, had been listed in serious but stable condition since he was moved 
recently from the surgical intensive care unit at Huntington Memorial Hospital 
to a private room. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's definitely doing better," said trainer Randy Bradshaw, a former Lukas 
assistant and family friend. "He did have some help brushing his teeth and 
shaving, but that's certainly to be expected. 
</P>
<P>
 "He's still very weak, but I'm sure he'll continue to get stronger. Being in 
bed for 30 days takes its toll, your muscles deteriorate. It'll take time to 
get his strength back." 
</P>
<P>
 Lukas is the only son of Eclipse Award-winning trainer Wayne Lukas, who said 
Wednesday that Jeff had been taken off all life-support systems and he had 
gradually come out of his coma. 
</P>
