<P>
BRIEFCASE: ADDING PLAY TIME 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by Anne Michaud, Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jim deYong, the "d" in dGWB, is heading into semi-retirement next week at the 
tender age of 45. The executive vice president of the award-winning Irvine ad 
agency will take on a role akin to permanent consultant and a tongue-in-cheek 
title of chairman emeritus. 
</P>
<P>
 deYong said he plans to travel to Central America, build a home in Dana Point, 
learn to golf and chip away at a list of about 50 things he's always wanted to 
do. A self-described workaholic, deYong has built three ad agencies in Orange 
County since 1976. He has been weaning himself from his role in new business 
development for about two years, he said, and he is proud to be leaving the 
agency on a high note, competing for business with such international 
heavyweights as Ketchum Advertising and Backer Spielvogel Bates. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a lot more fun batting in the big leagues," said the San Juan Capistrano 
resident. "I'll miss it, but I don't see myself coming back." 
