<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: GARDEN GROVE; CITY APPROVES COSTCO DEVELOPMENT PACT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ROBERT BARKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The City Council this week approved final terms of a development agreement 
that will allow the Costco Wholesale Corp. membership store to move to a larger 
location on a 13 1/2-acre parcel that the Agency for Community Development owns 
near the Garden Grove Freeway. 
</P>
<P>
 The council on Tuesday approved on a 4-1 vote final development fees totaling 
$695,000 for the move from the store's current location at 11822 Gilbert St. 
Officials said, however, that more than half the development fees imposed this 
week will be reimbursed to Costco by the Agency for Community Development, the 
city's redevelopment agency, after the store opens. 
</P>
<P>
 Costco officials plan to construct a 156,000-square-foot building on land 
south of Garden Grove Boulevard and west of Euclid Street. 
</P>
<P>
 The future Costco store will include new and expanded services such as a 
pharmacy, deli, nursery sales and a tire service center. 
</P>
<P>
 City officials estimate that Costco will double annual sales because it will 
be near the freeway and is expected to increase its regional drawing power. 
This would result in annual sales tax revenue to the city of $540,000 in the 
third year of operation and approximately $13 million over 20 years, according 
to officials. 
</P>
<P>
 Officials predict that the center will produce 50 to 75 full- and part-time 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
 The agency has spent about $9.9 million to buy lots and clear the site for the 
new store. But the net cost, because the city is trading for the land that 
Costco owns at its current location, is $6.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Robert F. Dinsen cast the only vote against the agreement, claiming 
the agency is paying too high a subsidy for the move. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Mark Leyes said that Costco officials needed a bigger store with 
more visibility to compete with rival stores. 
</P>
<P>
 Costco will continue operations at its current site during construction. 
Costco will pay rent of $29,167 a month to the agency for community development 
until leaving the building. 
</P>
<P>
 The main entry and exit for the new store will be at Garden Grove Boulevard 
and Main Street.ROBERT BARKER 
</P>
</TEXT>
